      "writtenOn": "2020-07-28T14:12:18Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Sorry I wasn\u0027t around to comment on this yesterday. My thoughts:\n\n1) I\u0027m guessing this is primarily for XCode? Visual Studio \u0026 VSCode support .natvis, which I\u0027ve got configured to show these types. It looks like LLDB has something similar (https://lldb.llvm.org/use/variable.html), but from what I can tell, it only affects \u0027print\u0027 commands in the LLDB interactive window in XCode, not any watch windows or hover? Bleh.\n\n2) Like Mike, I\u0027d be more interested in moving towards using standard containers all the time. Not sure of the best solution to SkSTArray - any of the proposed solutions (absl, pmr) is still going to have the same issue with debugging that led to this CL, right? But I think that moving SkTArray usage to std::vector (including understanding if/why there\u0027s any performance regression) is helpful. I also think that at least some of our SkSTArray usage is unnecessary (or actually misguided).",
      "revId": "f2c235f6275ac1338adfd981f72b903093fbc4bd",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "113287cc_69869498",
        "filename": "/PATCHSET_LEVEL",
        "patchSetId": 30
      },
      "lineNbr": 0,
      "author": {
        "id": 5045
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-07-28T14:17:03Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I wouldn\u0027t think an approach like std::pmr would affect debugging.  All you need to do is change the allocator, not std::vector.  (std::pmr::vector is an alias for std::vector with a flexible allocator, not a new type.)\n\nIf backporting all of std::pmr is too daunting, I think we can write a single focused allocator that uses stack until it runs out, then heap.  That\u0027s a subset of what std::pmr can do.",
      "parentUuid": "d481a2d4_594ee4ed",
      "revId": "f2c235f6275ac1338adfd981f72b903093fbc4bd",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "c1bb3d9e_cafaf664",
        "filename": "/PATCHSET_LEVEL",
        "patchSetId": 30
      },
      "lineNbr": 0,
      "author": {
        "id": 11059
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-07-28T14:22:52Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I haven\u0027t used pmr before so I\u0027m not too familiar with its ups and downs. \n\nI\u0027m a little concerned about operations that expect TArrays and STArrays to interoperate seamlessly--e.g.we support swapping a TArray with an STArray efficiently (see https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/master:third_party/skia/tests/TArrayTest.cpp;l\u003d97?q\u003d%22static%20void%20test_swap%22\u0026ss\u003dchromium ). If the allocator is baked into the type, that might not be implementable as-is. Maybe we just decide those cases are rare and not worth optimizing for?",
      "parentUuid": "113287cc_69869498",
      "revId": "f2c235f6275ac1338adfd981f72b903093fbc4bd",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "cab1494b_c4c05301",
        "filename": "/PATCHSET_LEVEL",
        "patchSetId": 30
      },
      "lineNbr": 0,
      "author": {
        "id": 11059
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-07-28T14:41:32Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Re Brian\u0027s original comments.\n\n#1 - I believe we can make LLDB visualizers work with Xcode, and that\u0027s a good plan B if this doesn\u0027t work out for some reason\n\n#2 - I totally agree. In the long run I would love to get rid of custom containers unless they offer some staggering advantage that can\u0027t be solved any other way. I\u0027ve been down this road before and I expect that to be a long-term effort where we make slow incremental progress towards that goal. I see this CL as part of that small incremental progress. If nothing else, it exposes a lot of cases where SkTArray papered over issues that vector\u003c\u003e would not allow (e.g. missing move constructors/assignment, missing #includes, `const` inhibiting std::move, etc) and hopefully prevents backsliding on that front.",
      "parentUuid": "c1bb3d9e_cafaf664",
      "revId": "f2c235f6275ac1338adfd981f72b903093fbc4bd",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "4b919f40_1f11978c",
