      "writtenOn": "2020-07-28T15:05:42Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Ignoring the hard work you\u0027ve done, is there any reason not to treat #1 as plan A?",
      "parentUuid": "cab1494b_c4c05301",
      "revId": "f2c235f6275ac1338adfd981f72b903093fbc4bd",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "60d8467a_8f76893e",
        "filename": "/PATCHSET_LEVEL",
        "patchSetId": 30
      },
      "lineNbr": 0,
      "author": {
        "id": 11059
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-07-28T15:26:37Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I think it would be fantastic if we had LLDB visualizers for all of our low-level types. I wasn\u0027t actually aware that we had Natvis visualizers either--I asked some folks when I joined about this, and I guess I asked the wrong folks, because I was led to believe we didn\u0027t have any debug visualizers.\n\nThat being said, if we agree that standard containers are a worthy goal, I think this CL gives us a foothold in that world, and it also solves the debuggability issue in a universal, platform-neutral way. It\u0027s not hard to imagine a hypothetical future where we decide to migrate off SkTArray and use this implementation as a stopgap during the migration (since it can seamlessly convert to and from vector). That\u0027s ambitious, though, and will take a lot of SWE time that we may decide to direct elsewhere. It won\u0027t happen overnight. For now, I\u0027m just trying to avoid overpromising.",
      "parentUuid": "4b919f40_1f11978c",
      "revId": "f2c235f6275ac1338adfd981f72b903093fbc4bd",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "a908010e_ad514a89",
        "filename": "/PATCHSET_LEVEL",
        "patchSetId": 30
      },
      "lineNbr": 0,
      "author": {
        "id": 5631
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-07-28T17:03:50Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I think my other hesitation with this CL is that it\u0027s going to create a maintenance burden, and that burden is probably going to fall on John, unless anyone else is going to start using this mode. Without this mode enabled on a bot, or by default, the rest of the team is going to re-break the assumptions here (adding an SkTArray\u003cbool\u003e, or using MEM_MOVE over-eagerly, etc...).\n\n... And I don\u0027t want to advocate for adding a bot, because then everyone does need to avoid re-breaking this, despite the fact that nearly all of the team won\u0027t be using it.\n\nIf we really want to move towards standard containers, I\u0027d be much happier to just start replacing uses of SkTArray, and punt on SkSTArray for now. If do that, the one-off fixes for stored types (not being properly move-able, etc...) are clearly tied to the refactor of the relevant code.",
      "revId": "f2c235f6275ac1338adfd981f72b903093fbc4bd",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "e8444a73_b84926bb",
        "filename": "/PATCHSET_LEVEL",
        "patchSetId": 30
      },
      "lineNbr": 0,
      "author": {
        "id": 11059
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-07-28T17:19:17Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I can focus my energy on making an LLDB visualizer if we think that\u0027s a better use of time. I\u0027m not too worried about maintenance cost, personally--I fixed up 15 years of SkTArray usage in a little over a day--but I can understand the desire to minimize it.\n\nAm I really the only team member who would enable this feature? What does the rest of the team do for debugging? Do our Linux users already have a convenient way to visualize arrays? Does the team generally avoid gdb/lldb, or just endure manual print statements/memory dumps? I don\u0027t have a feeling for the team culture here (WFH...).\n\nIf we try to replace SkTArray objects one by one, I would be concerned that eventually we would hit a wall where switching things piecemeal becomes increasingly difficult due to lack of interop between SkTArray and vector without expensive copies. This class gives us a \"toll-free bridging\" solution (to steal a CoreFoundation term). That\u0027s not something we necessarily need right away, but it\u0027s certainly nice to have.",
      "parentUuid": "a908010e_ad514a89",
      "revId": "f2c235f6275ac1338adfd981f72b903093fbc4bd",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
